\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 1. A. hybridus} L., {\i Sp. Pl.} 990 (1753) ({\i A. patulus} auct., non Bertol.,{\i  A. chlorostachys} Willd.). Stems 20-100 cm, erect, sparsely to densely pubescent above. Leaves 3-8 cm, rhombic-ovate. Inflorescence elongate-spicate, often compound, with long branches. Bracteoles (2-)3-4 mm, ovate, with a very long mucro, about twice as long as the perianth. Perianth-segments 5, 1·5-2(-2·4) mm, narrowly ovate, usually acute, about as long as the fruit. Stamens 5. Fruit dehiscing transversely. 2n = 32.{\i  Commonly naturalized in many parts of Europe}. [Al Au Az Bl Br Bu Co Cr Cz Ga Ge Gr He Hs Hu It Ju Lu Po Rm Rs(K) Sa Si.] ({\i Tropical and subtropical America}.)
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 There has been considerable taxonomic and nomenclatural confusion between species {\b 1-3} which has arisen because of the great level of phenotypic plasticity in these species, hybridization with each other and other species (especially{\b  4}), and the naming of taxa in the Old and New Worlds without reference to the total pattern of variation. The geographical distributions of these species reported here must therefore be regarded as provisional.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 Their taxonomy is summarized in J.D. Sauer,{\i  loc. cit.} (1967).
\par

